Desain ini adalah pengganti dari original Prusa i3 Rework

Problem umum di Prusa i3 Rework:

  1. Dudukan J-head hotend stuck, terkunci di dalam lubang bodi extruder
  2. Hanya ada satu fan, kurang bagus untuk print PLA/flex
  3. Lubang supply filamen kecil, kadang kurang lancar ketika deformasi (misal karena kepanasan)
  4. Kesulitan membuka jendela idler untuk memasukkan filamen
  5. Belum ada tempat khusus untuk proximity sensor
  6. Sering gagal ketika print flex
  7. Hotend e3d V5 terlalu panjang, sehingga endstop original tidak menyentuh limit switch original. Print area Z lebih pendek +- 1cm

Desain update ini menjawab semua permasalahan tersebut.
Note: Selipkan selang PTFE ID2 OD4 ke dalam lubang supply filamen

This design is a replacement of the original Prusa i3 Rework

Common Problems in Prusa i3 Rework:

J-head holder hotend stuck, locked in the extruder body hole
There is only one fan, less good for PLA / flex print
Small filament supply hole, sometimes less smoothly when deformation (eg due to overheating)
Difficulty opening the idler window to insert the filament
There is no specific place for proximity sensor
Often fails when print flex
Hotend e3d V5 is too long, so the original endstop does not touch the original switch limit. Print area Z is shorter + - 1cm
This update design answers all the problems.
Note: Insert the PTFE ID2 OD4 hose into the filament supply hole

The original Prusa i3 Rework Extruder can gound here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:119616

description.text:
Designed for my .22 caliber Gamo Raptor Whisper air rifle. Picatinny rail for my laser light, camera base on the left, and easily accessible rounds located convenient to the breech on the break barrel design.

The barrel clamp bolts down using a standard gopro nut and bolt handle thing.

The .22 caliber slots hold pellets where they are perfectly accessible to load the break barrel design on the gamo air rifle. The cover is magnetically held in place keeping the pellets from sliding out. The latch swings down touching the barrel to slide a pellet out, then the latch closes to a magnet holder. There are 2X3mm recesses to glue in magnets linked below.

Gopro mount is for a screw-on base, you slide a 1/4" bolt of appropriate length in there and thread the camera mount down. I will modify it for a gopro clip base soon if there is interest.

This is my first ever build project to learn how to use sketchup. I am waiting on my first 3d printer to arrive to run this through. I don't know any better but the layers in cura look like they should work.

This was designed specifically for a Gamo Raptor Whisper 1" barrel with a small notch running the barrel to keep it aligned. I can modify it for different calibers and barrel requirements if there is interest. Let me know what you think! Thanks for looking!

I made this 100% from scratch without any visual aid besides the accessories I want to attach and a caliper.

description.text:
I love the hitch design by fwillburn but was bothered by the fact it did not properly cover the hitch. This remix includes a 5mm wall after the logo closing the hitch mount.

The disadvantage of this design is a single color will wash out the logo. Therefore it is preferred to print in two colors. The logo ends exactly 10mm. The wall begins at that point. So you can change filament at 10 mm as shown in my pictures.

The design contains the square of the hitch mount embedded into the logo. Therefore, swapping out the color at the end of the logo print causes the square to be printed in the same color. Not a big deal but not perfect (see my pictures). An alternative is to print 5mm then swap. So the back of the log is the same color as the hitch mount.

comments.text: Oh...as for problems I had with the print...stringing was an issue. Set your retraction to at least 10mm per retraction and it should minimize that. I also used a few quick swipes through the airways with my heat gun on the low setting to clean up the internal stringing and then used the tiny flathead screwdriver provided with the Tarantula kit to scrape out the leftover plastic snot-balls that formed after the heat gun passes I made. If you use the heat gun method to do cleanup it becomes a snap for the most part. Just make sure you don't go too slow over the part or you'll warp it or worse. Also, don't make the same mistake I made by holding the part by hand while making heat gun passes (That thing burns skin pretty quick...my thumb still has a blister from it).

title: Monoprice MP Select Mini Z Axis Adjustable Endstop

description.text:
An adjustable Z endstop for the Monoprice Select Mini / Mayan M200. No more need to adjust the bed level screws and install spacers if you are printing on glass, swapping nozzles, doing maintenance, or trying to fine tuning your first layer.

No major modifications or drilling required.

Re-positions the z-endstop switch closer to the bed where a bracket with an adjustment screw can trigger it.

Parts Needed:

  • M3 Nut
  • M3 Screw (20mm or longer)
  • Small Spring: Can be sourced from a clicker pen and cut down if too long/stiff.
  • M3 Washer: To keep the spring from binding on the head of the screw.

Reused:

  • Limit switch M2 screws and nuts
  • X carriage shield plastic screw

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

50% +

Notes:

Model is optimized for .4 nozzle, .4 extrustion width. 3 perimeter, 4 top/bottom.

Tested in both PLA and Petg. PLA is more slippery when clamped against the smooth painted metal of the printer frame.

Fitment is intentionally tight to prevent wobble or play, make sure everything is seated tight and doesn't move or wiggle.

In operation

Prep Requirements: Remove the X-carriage shield and remount X limit switch if necessary.
Some of the printers come with the X limit switch mounted directly to the carriage, later ones come with the switch mounted to the metal shield.
If yours is mounted to the shield, you'll need to print an adapter:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1761961
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2045548

Install:

  • Raise the X carriage to the top of the printer before you begin.

  • Remove the front metal cover from the tower. Leave the rear cover on.

Limit Switch

  • Unscrew the Z endstop. Check to make sure the wires are long enough top reach the new position without interfering with the Z Stepper/lead screw.

  • Clear out the nut and screw holes in the printed parts. Press fit the M2 Nuts into the endstop bracket.

  • Fit the switch and loosely screw the assembly together

  • Plug in the switch and route the wires away from the threaded rod and stepper.

  • Slot the switch assembly over the rear tower cover. Hold down tight in place and clamp with the screws, making sure its fully seated flush and doesn't wiggle/move. If it wiggles or has play, try adding tape on the metal or between for added friction/thickness.

Adjustment Bracket

  • Tilt the machine over on its side ( on the filament side) , X carriage pointed up.

  • Test fit the bracket, it should seat tightly and not wiggle even before being screwed down.

  • Clean out the m3 screw nut and screw hole. The M3 screw should be able to move/spin freely in the hole without binding on plastic.

  • Press fit the M3 nut. Assemble the Spring ,washer, screw combo and thread through bracket. Tighten Down as far as the spring will allow, making sure at least 1cm is below the nut.

  • Press the bracket in the carriage and screw down reusing the x carriage shield screw. (6mm long plastic screw) Make sure there is zero play in the bracket, it should seat tight without wiggling.

  • Reinstall front tower cover to make sure everything clears.

Adjustment

  • Start with the screw all the way down and no glass on the bed.

  • Home the printer and see how close the nozzle gets.

  • Each complete turn of the adjustment screw raises or lowers home position by .5mm ( .5 thread pitch). Small adjustments are can be made : 1/10th turn = .05mm

  • Back the adjustment screw out and rehome until the correct height.

title: Anet a8 bed frame supports(for cnc upgrade)

description.text:
I found out the anet installation video is wrong my bed is upside down It will work the same reversed just dont use photo as a reference...
The stl is up there for the idea i dont know if it will hold up with the bed heating up...
Ive been wanting to do this once i actually needed to take apart the heating bed assembly to repack the bearings..
The reason i made it is because if you look at your beds aluminum frame you might notice a slight bow or bend because of the lack of support there so every time you tighten the belt the frame is actually bending down...This will straighten it out and strengthen the frame since and im taking every measure so i can machine stuff with more confidence on the anet...

The photos are from 5mm plexi or 1/4 inch thick plexi glass...
since I have alot of scrap pcs i figured id save the filament and use what i have since this is a hefty build for 3dprinters...
Also I would recommend plexi or aluminum if you have it.. I left the vectors if you want to machine it...
Installation video https://youtu.be/x-Moko1oc_g
Installation
pre drill and tap the holes on the aluminum frame with a 3.2 or 1/8" mm drill bit with 4mm tap for m4 screw threading.... but you can just drill thru the frame and use a nut or bolt..
Just be wary of the screws coming out to far on the bottom of the frame the clearance is around 4 or 5mm to the plexi..
Check the installation video for futher explaination

Enjoy

comments.text: The video is wrong. The cross-member needs to be UNDER the side-rails. REASON: Putting the cross-member under the side-rails makes the y-axis belt parallel.  With the cross-member ABOVE the side rails, the belt is above parallel where the belts connect under it.

comments.text: The reason that the frame is bending when you apply tension to the y-axis is because you have the frame on upside down.  The Anet video and pdf file have you install it upside down.  In this orientation the y-axis belt angles up toward the bed, thus pulling it down under tension.  If you flip the frame over you will see that the belt is now parallel to the y-axis and won't have a vertical component to pull on the frame.

This is a combination of all of the mods that I wanted to have on my x-carriage using a hotend.com hotend. 1 It uses linear bearing LM8UU
2 In good offroad fashion I gave it a 3 cm lift kit :)
3 It has an integrated ducted fan
4 The extruder is shifted on the carriage for a better CofG
5 The belt is a little closer to the center so that the extruder can move higher before the belt touches This thing is sure smooth!

This thing has already been printed and tested. I've uploaded a final version, printed it out and used it. Everything fits and works. One important thing to mention is that this is designed to the hotend.com MkIV hotend. It is a little longer and if people want, I'll re-design it for MakerGear hotends, too. This new x-carriage should give a 120 mm Z-height using a MG hotend if it is redesigned. Let me know if you want one made for a MakerGear Prusa. For now, you can use the non-lifted, non-linear bearing but ducted fan x-carriage of mine at: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16558 I can now print objects somewhere around 100mm tall!! :D (I've checked for an exact height before the belt touches and the belt touches at ~ 110 mm.) The image posted is of my prototype in action. The hotend is now centered in front of the fan duct. Other small cosmetic changes have been also made but are minor. This design can use the MakerGear belt clamps and MakerGear hardware. The linear bears are LM8UU. The spacing for the fan screws fit a common 40mm fan. I still need to re-design the x-carriage pulley so that it sits closer to the X centerline and design standoffs to reposition the X-motor so that it lines up better for a straighter belt path. I have added a link to a photo that shows vertex, belt and frame clearances. These pics are of my printer with the currently uploaded STL. The x-carriage is fitted with a hotends.com hotend and the x-carriage is 90 mm above the build bed. One new vertex must be designed to allow a 110 + mm print height. Please let me know what you think about it. Enjoy, J

title: einfacher Anet A8 Raspberry-Halter  simple raspberry-frame

description.text:
Einfacher Rahmen um den Raspberry-Pi (B,B+,2) außen am Gestell des Anet-A8 zu montieren.

Version 1 ist mit Sechskanttaschen zur Aufnahme eines SW5 Gewindesockels, wie er früher viel zu Montage von Motherboards in PCs verwendet wurde (siehe Foto) Außengewinde absägen und sechskant in den Frame einsetzen. Er ragt dann 2mm über, so dass unter dem Raspberry genug Platz ist.

Version 2 hat 2mm Pads zum Aufsetzen des Raspberry auf der Vorderseite und hinten SW5,5 Sechskantlöcher zum Einsetzen einer M3 Mutter, so dass die Gewindesockel nicht benötigt werden.

This is a simple frame to mount a Raspberry-Pi (B,B+,2) on an Anet A8 printer.
V1 is to use with 5mm nuts on the front, often used to mount motherboards to PC-cases. (see Foto). Just cut off the little thread and put the nut into the frame.

V2 is with 2mm pads on the front to put the raspberry on and 5.5mm nut-holes for M3 nuts in the back.

description.text:
A tool rack that accommodates all of the tools that come included with the Form2 3D Printer from Formlabs. I have also created a removable drip tray that clips in underneath the rack to catch any drips that come off the tools once they have been inserted. The Tray slopes very slightly towards the front so that excessive resin drips would collect towards the front making it easier to see and clean up.

I printed this upside down as shown in the screenshot at a resolution of 0.1mm, I would however recommend that you print it the right way up as the supports pit the face of the stand excessively and will require additional finishing.

The drip tray is totally optional and does not need to be printed in order to use this stand. It has space for the scraper, pry tool, angled snips, and also the tweezers.

Printer Brand:

Formlabs

Printer:

Formlabs Form 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.05

Notes:

I would recommend printing this in the final orientation, only because I printed it upside down to save on support material, however, because printing upside down means it is an aesthetic face where all of the support structure meets the model it just wrecks the face and needs a ton more post processing and finishing to bring the surface back up to a quality surface; where as if you print it in the correct orientation all the support structure meets the underside so it's less of an issue if the surfaces aren't 100%.

Just a bit of a light sanding to remove any support blemishes. There is around about a 0.5mm clearance between the drip tray locking wings and the slots in the stand so it's not too much of a drama to just slot them together, depending on your printer/print settings though it may need a very light sand to get the fit just right.

remixed_from.title: The UnLimbited Arm v2.1 - Alfie Edition

description.text:
This is a Remix of the Phoenix Hand & UnLimbited Arm, designed by Albert Fung. This project is a collaboration between e-NABLE Sierra Leone and the Hong Kong Maker Club.

It became apparent in our previous feasibility study that for the 3D printed prosthetics to survive the tropics, we need to remove components that are not well-adapted to hot weather. We therefore set out to replace all the rubber bands in the Phoenix hand.

Palm: We used the One-Arm palm designed by below_cho as out starting point. All the cable tunnels have been widened, the knuckle stumps removed, and a bar is added at the thumb base for tying elastic cord.

Palm mesh: we have modified the thick palm mesh by John Diamond to strengthen the screw holes.

Fingers: Tunnels have been created so an elastic cord can now run all the way from the finger tip up into the palm.

Pins: For snug fitting, some of the pins have been resized and reshaped.

Hope you'll find this new remix useful!

Ed Choi

::: Construction notes :::

For a wrist-powered prosthetic hand, please use the Reborn Hand with a thermal gauntlet.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:864030 and tensioner/tensioner pins from the Raptor Reloaded. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:596966

For an elbow-powered prosthetic arm, please use the Reborn palm with the "forearm" and bicep "cuff" from the UnLimbited Arm (see link). There is a glitch in the Thingiverse Customizer, so you will need to set the UnLimbited "hand length" to at least 145mm. Otherwise the forearm wrist joint would not be wide enough to fit into the palm.

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1672381
http://www.teamunlimbited.org/the-unlimbited-arm-20-alfie-edition-current/

We printed the Reborn hand at 124% and used it with parametric forearm, cuff and tensioner pins from the UnLimbited Arm(v2.0). From our field experience, the UnLimbited Arm cuff pins are not stronger enough to hold the elbow in place for very long. So we advice everyone to use Chicago/binding screws (glued) instead.

Scaling the ReBorn Hand parts at 124% would give you:

Palm width (widest): 80mm
Wrist joint (outside): 75mm
Wrist joint (inside): 64mm

Reassure R2 - full thread woodscrew 3.0 x 16mm

5) Silicone fingertip grips - Tipper Lee, and superglued to secure them to the fingers

6) Velcro - 1 inch thick double-sided

description.text:
This is a fan shroud for the inexpensive HP DPS-700GB hot swappable server power supply. It's a great supply for many applications up to 700W and voltage can be tuned to about 13.5v.

The power supply does not come with a fan, as it relies on the server's fans, so you must supply your own. It will otherwise overheat on idle.

I use this to power 2x ISDT SC-608. Since they require about 13.4v to get full 150W power output, I added a 1.3kOhm voltage adjustment resistor, which boosts voltage to about 13.5v.
You may use something like a 2kOhm resistor for closer to 12.7v, or neglect the resistor entirely to use just about ~12v. This will be enough to power the ISDT SC-608 at about 120W.

I charge at 8C sometimes so I chose to add the resistor.

Requires:
1x HP DPS-700GB 700W PSU
2x M3x6 screws
1x M3 nut
1x standard 80mm x 80mm x 25mm fan
(optional) 2x M4x30 screws
(optional) 2x M4 nuts
(optional) 1.3kOhm resistor

The tolerances are designed so that the fan press fits into the mount. However, M4 mounting holes are included in the print. The print needs just minimal support for the screw mounts.

To mount the shroud, simply screw in the M3 screws as in the picture. The top M3 is threaded into the PSU, but the side M3 screw hole is not threaded, so you will need to use a nut.

Included is a partial pinout.
You must bridge the 3 marked connections to turn the power supply on.
I soldered the voltage adjustment resistor for 13.5v.
Next I soldered power out connections; the holes on bottom are for your wires out, and they will fit an XT60 connector, but it's recommended you thread your wires through the holes before soldering. I believe the 12v rails are separate, so distribute power draw accordingly. I would keep power draw to 15A per pair of pads, but you may easily parallel pads on top/bottom.
Finally, I installed my fan and then soldered the wires to the 10v rail, for slightly lower noise. Remember that the fan wires must go inside the shroud before you solder or you will not be able to wire it in.

Please let me know if you have any questions or issues. Printed on a Lulzbot Taz6 with .5mm nozzle head and .35mm layer height.
